Attempting to pull VertexBuffer Data results in null reference exception. We are using the data to build a bounding box around a model.

Attached below is the function we are using:-

Attempting to use the following function fails on the line "meshPart.VertexBuffer.GetData<float>(vertexData);" 

```
 private float GetWidth(string word)
    {
        foreach (ModelMesh mesh in Model.Meshes)
        {
            foreach (ModelMeshPart meshPart in mesh.MeshParts)
            {
                int vertexStride = meshPart.VertexBuffer.VertexDeclaration.VertexStride;
                int vertexBufferSize = meshPart.NumVertices * vertexStride;

                float[] vertexData = new float[vertexBufferSize / sizeof(float)];
                meshPart.VertexBuffer.GetData<float>(vertexData);

                for (int i = 0; i < vertexBufferSize / sizeof(float); i += vertexStride / sizeof(float))
                {
                    Vector3 transformedPosition = Vector3.Transform(new Vector3(vertexData[i], vertexData[i + 1], vertexData[i + 2]), Globals.WorldMatrix);

                    min = Vector3.Min(min, transformedPosition);
                    max = Vector3.Max(max, transformedPosition);
                }
            }
        }

        HitBox = new BoundingBox(min, max);

        return (word.Contains(" ") ? max.X + 0.7f : max.X);
    }
```

I have two separate BasicEffect objects.  At the moment they are identical save for their transformations; while one has the camera matrices (view/projection) set, the other BasicEffect is all identity as it's used for drawing some batched billboards with lots of CPU-side processing in NDC space.

The specific combination of properties is:
LightingEnabled = false;
TextureEnabled = false;
VertexColorEnabled = true;

If I Apply the first BasicEffect, draw my world geometry, then Apply the other BasicEffect and draw my billboards, they're transformed by the matrices in the first.  Had a look at the code, and making any change to either BasicEffect that changes its shaderIndex (such as disabling vertex color) fixes it.  I assume that something somewhere is looking at the two BasicEffects, believing them to be equal and skipping the Apply calls completely rather than just the shader switch.

The above method throws an exception because _vertexBuffer._type is not a value type (it's a VertexDeclaration)

//before
            var vd = VertexDeclaration.FromType(_vertexBuffer._type);
            VertexDeclaration.PrepareForUse(vd, IntPtr.Zero);
//after
            VertexDeclaration.PrepareForUse(_vertexBuffer.VertexDeclaration, IntPtr.Zero);

Not sure if this is an appropriate change or not, but the test code which on MacOS shows a rectangle shows nothing at all on iOS.

Is basic 3D supported for iOS? Is there a working example somewhere?

Thanks
